{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_91","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc 'for f in code/*/README.md; do echo \"===== $f\"; rg -n \"''^(#|##|###)|Usage|Setup|Installation|Install|Data|Dataset|Benchmark|Run|python|pip|conda|OPENAI|ANTHROPIC|S2|Semantic|grobid|API|download|requirements\" \"$f\" | sed -n '\"'1,80p'; done\"","aggregated_output":"===== code/ai_idea_bench_2025/README.md\n2:  <b>AI Idea Bench 2025: AI Research Idea Generation Benchmark</b><br>\n7:  🤗 <a href=\"https://huggingface.co/datasets/yanshengqiu/AI_Idea_Bench_2025\">[Dataset]</a>\n11:## 💬 Introduction\n13:### Benchmark\n15:### Evaluation Framework\n19:## 🚀 Pipline\n21:### Create the enviroment\n24:pip install requirements.txt\n27:### Data preparation\n46:### Preparation for SciPDF Parser:\n47:Install [SciPDF Parser](https://github.com/titipata/scipdf_parser) for PDF parsing.\n50:pip install git+https://github.com/titipata/scipdf_parser\n51:python -m spacy download en_core_web_sm\n54:### Preparation for grobid:\n55:Install java for grobid\n57:wget  https://download.oracle.com/java/GA/jdk11/9/GPL/openjdk-11.0.2_linux-x64_bin.tar.gz\n62:### Run grobid\n64:If you can successfully start grobid in [SciPDF Parser](https://github.com/titipata/scipdf_parser.git), run the following commands:\n67:bash serve_grobid.sh\n70:(Optional) Or, you can refer to the following process to install grobid if the previous commands fail:\n72:git clone https://github.com/kermitt2/grobid.git\n73:cd grobid\n78:### Generate ideas\n88:Set your code paths, semantic scholar API, GPT-4o API, deepseek API, output file paths in generate_ideas_fron_papers.py lines 16, 472-476, 482-484, 494, and 507-512.\n92:python generate_ideas_fron_papers.py\n98:### Idea multiple-choice evaluation\n105:python Make_MCQ.py # Make mcq questions\n111:python MCQ.py\n115:### Idea to idea matching\n120:python idea_gt_idea.py\n123:### Idea to idea matching\n128:python idea_gt_topic.py\n131:### Ideas competition among baselines\n136:python competition.py\n140:### Novelty assessment\n142:Set semantic scholar API in find_paper_by_kewords.py lines 16\n145:python find_paper_by_kewords.py  # Find curren papers and history papers\n150:python extract_hd_cd_paper.py\n152:**Attention !!** Here there may be a failure to parse the paper, this is because some papers cannot be downloaded through the script. For this issue, we will manually re-download those papers that cannot be parsed.\n158:python Novelty.py\n161:### Feasibility\n166:python split_experimental_plan.py  # split experimental plan of generated ideas\n171:### Novelty assessment\n173:Set semantic scholar API in feasibility.py lines 12\n176:python feasibility.py \n179:## 🚩 License\n183:## 📜 Citations\n186:  title={AI Idea Bench 2025: AI Research Idea Generation Benchmark},\n192:## 🔈 Acknowledgements\n===== code/ai_researcher_human_study/README.md\n2:  <b>Research Ideation Agent & Human Study Data</b><br>\n18:## Table of Contents\n21:2. [Ideation Study Data](#ideation-study-data)\n22:3. [Execution Study Data](#execution-study-data)\n24:## Ideation Agent Implementation\n28:Our agent pipeline consists of the following modules:\n36:These modules are designed to be run sequentially as an end-to-end idea generation pipeline. Each module can also be run separately as standalone research assistance tools. We describe how to run each module as well as the entire pipeline below.\n38:1. [Setup](#setup)\n45:8. [End-to-End Pipeline](#end-to-end-pipeline)\n48:### Setup\n55:conda create -n ai-researcher python=3.10\n56:conda activate ai-researcher\n57:pip install -r requirements.txt\n64:    \"api_key\": \"Your OpenAI API Key\",\n66:    \"s2_key\": \"Your Semantic Scholar API Key (Optional)\",\n67:    \"anthropic_key\": \"Your Anthropic API Key\"\n71:### Related Paper Search\n73:The related work search module will iteratively propose search queries and search through the Semantic Scholar API. We then use an LLM to score the relevance of retrieved papers for reranking. The module takes a topic description or an idea as input and returns a list of the most relevant papers as output.\n81:The `max_paper_bank_size` is a hyperparameter to control when to stop the paper search process (until the specified number of papers has been retrieved). The generated search queries as well as the ranked papers will be stored in the specified cache file. The cache file can be used as part of the input to the idea generation module. We used `max_paper_bank_size=120` for the experiments in our paper and used `max_paper_bank_size=50` in this demo example. Running this demo example costs $0.51. \n84:### Grounded Idea Generation\n96:### Idea Deduplication\n98:We do a round of deduplication to remove similar ideas generated by the grounded idea generation module. We set a threshold of `similarity_threshold=0.8` cosine similarity based on the sentence embeddings to determine if two ideas are similar. The embedding is from the `sentence-transformers` library so this step doesn't cost any API credits to run.\n106:### Project Proposal Generation\n118:### Project Proposal Ranking\n130:### Project Proposal Filtering (Optional)\n142:### End-to-End Pipeline\n144:We also provide a script that runs the entire pipeline to generate the project proposals based on the given research topic.\n153:## Ideation Study Data\n159:- All the ideas in the Human Condition can be downloaded from [this link](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1Z2Nd7WNNks-eCoqUgPzx1_ovYqU8OiPx/view?usp=sharing).\n161:- All the ideas in the AI Condition can be downloaded from [this link](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1AFjSUCTj4wL081R2b17nVuNSs7xvzh8F/view?usp=sharing).\n163:- All ideas in the AI + Human Rerank Condition can be downloaded from [this link](https://drive.google.com/file/d/15r3TzFd-6dPXdSMx0shZ4q3ljDOEzp8I/view?usp=sharing).\n165:## Execution Study Data\n169:All the edited ideas (with executors' proposed changes), papers, and codebases can be downloaded from [this link](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1PpxeTz_-xHHcMXyUwv1Oed1avTaiD5vv/view?usp=sharing).\n173:## Citation\n===== code/ai_scientist/README.md\n21:2. [Multi-scale Grid Noise Adaptation: Enhancing Diffusion Models For Low-dimensional Data](https://github.com/SakanaAI/AI-Scientist/blob/main/example_papers/grid_based_noise_adaptation.pdf)\n29:10. [Accelerating Mathematical Insight: Boosting Grokking Through Strategic Data Augmentation](https://github.com/SakanaAI/AI-Scientist/tree/main/example_papers/data_augmentation_grokking.pdf)\n38:## Table of Contents\n41:2. [Requirements](#requirements)\n42:   - [Installation](#installation)\n43:   - [Supported Models and API Keys](#supported-models-and-api-keys)\n48:4. [Run AI Scientist Paper Generation Experiments](#run-ai-scientist-paper-generation-experiments)\n57:## Introduction\n61:## Requirements\n63:This code is designed to run on Linux with NVIDIA GPUs using CUDA and PyTorch. Support for other GPU architectures may be possible by following the [PyTorch guidelines](https://pytorch.org/get-started/locally/). The current templates would likely take an infeasible amount of time on CPU-only machines. Running on other operating systems may require significant adjustments.\n65:### Installation\n68:conda create -n ai_scientist python=3.11\n69:conda activate ai_scientist\n70:# Install pdflatex\n73:# Install PyPI requirements\n74:pip install -r requirements.txt\n77:**Note:** Installing `texlive-full` can take a long time. You may need to [hold Enter](https://askubuntu.com/questions/956006/pregenerating-context-markiv-format-this-may-take-some-time-takes-forever) during the installation.\n79:### Supported Models and API Keys\n81:We support a wide variety of models, including open-weight and API-only models. In general, we recommend using only frontier models above the capability of the original GPT-4. To see a full list of supported models, see [here](https://github.com/SakanaAI/AI-Scientist/blob/main/ai_scientist/llm.py).\n83:#### OpenAI API (GPT-4o, GPT-4o-mini, o1 models)\n85:By default, this uses the `OPENAI_API_KEY` environment variable.\n87:#### Anthropic API (Claude Sonnet 3.5)\n89:By default, this uses the `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` environment variable.\n91:##### Claude Models via Bedrock\n96:pip install anthropic[bedrock]\n103:##### Claude Models via Vertex AI\n108:pip install google-cloud-aiplatform\n109:pip install anthropic[vertex]\n116:export ANTHROPIC_VERTEX_PROJECT_ID=\"PROJECT_ID\"  # for Model Garden call\n121:#### DeepSeek API (deepseek-chat, deepseek-reasoner)\n122:By default, this uses the `DEEPSEEK_API_KEY` environment variable.\n124:#### OpenRouter API (Llama3.1)\n126:By default, this uses the `OPENROUTER_API_KEY` environment variable.\n128:#### Google Gemini\n132:export GEMINI_API_KEY=[REDACTED]"YOUR GEMINI API KEY\"\n135:#### Semantic Scholar API (Literature Search)\n137:Our code can also optionally use a Semantic Scholar API Key (`S2_API_KEY`) for higher throughput [if you have one](https://www.semanticscholar.org/product/api), though it should work without it in principle. If you have problems with Semantic Scholar, you can skip the literature search and citation phases of paper generation.\n142:export OPENAI_API_KEY=[REDACTED]"YOUR KEY HERE\"\n143:export S2_API_KEY=\"YOUR KEY HERE\"\n146:#### OpenAlex API (Literature Search Alternative)\n148:OpenAlex API can be used as an alternative if you do not have a Semantic Scholar API Key.\n149:OpenAlex does not require API key.\n152:pip install pyalex\n158:Note that this is experimental for those who do not have a Semantic Scholar API Key.\n160:## Setting Up the Templates\n164:### NanoGPT Template\n168:**Setup Steps:**\n173:   python data/enwik8/prepare.py\n174:   python data/shakespeare_char/prepare.py\n175:   python data/text8/prepare.py\n184:   python experiment.py --out_dir run_0\n185:   python plot.py\n188:### 2D Diffusion Template\n192:**Setup Steps:**\n194:1. **Install dependencies:**\n200:   pip install .\n201:   pip install scikit-learn\n209:   python experiment.py --out_dir run_0\n210:   python plot.py\n213:### Grokking Template\n217:**Setup Steps:**\n219:1. **Install dependencies:**\n223:   pip install einops\n231:   python experiment.py --out_dir run_0\n232:   python plot.py\n235:## Run AI Scientist Paper Generation Experiments\n240:conda activate ai_scientist\n241:# Run the paper generation.\n242:python launch_scientist.py --model \"gpt-4o-2024-05-13\" --experiment nanoGPT_lite --num-ideas 2\n243:python launch_scientist.py --model \"claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022\" --experiment nanoGPT_lite --num-ideas 2\n248:## Getting an LLM-Generated Paper Review\n250:```python\n257:# Load paper from PDF file (raw text)\n260:# Get the review dictionary\n271:# Inspect review results\n281:python iclr_analysis.py --num_reviews 500 --batch_size 100 --num_fs_examples 1 --num_reflections 5 --temperature 0.1 --num_reviews_ensemble 5\n284:## Making Your Own Template\n297:### Community-Contributed Templates\n311:## Template Resources\n316:- **2D Diffusion Template** uses code from [tiny-diffusion](https://github.com/tanelp/tiny-diffusion), [ema-pytorch](https://github.com/lucidrains/ema-pytorch), and [Datasaur](https://www.research.autodesk.com/publications/same-stats-different-graphs/).\n===== code/coi_agent/README.md\n20:## 🔥 News\n24:## 🛠️ Requirements and Installation\n29:pip install -r requirements.txt\n33:Install [SciPDF Parser](https://github.com/titipata/scipdf_parser) for PDF parsing.\n36:pip install git+https://github.com/titipata/scipdf_parser\n37:python -m spacy download en_core_web_sm\n41:Install java for grobid\n43:wget  https://download.oracle.com/java/GA/jdk11/9/GPL/openjdk-11.0.2_linux-x64_bin.tar.gz\n49:set config.yaml to use the LLM APIs.\n51:# Sementic scholor api, it should be filled\n52:SEMENTIC_SEARCH_API_KEY: \"\"\n56:# set it if you set is_azure to True\n57:AZURE_OPENAI_ENDPOINT : \"\"\n58:AZURE_OPENAI_KEY : \"\"\n59:AZURE_OPENAI_API_VERSION : \"\"\n61:# set it if you set is_azure to False\n62:OPENAI_API_KEY: \"\"\n63:OPENAI_BASE_URL: \"\"\n65:# if not set it will be set to the same as main llm\n66:EMBEDDING_API_KEY: \"\"\n67:EMBEDDING_API_ENDPOINT: \"\"\n75:## 🚀 Quick Start\n76:**Step 1**: Run grobid\n78:If you can successfully start grobid in [SciPDF Parser](https://github.com/titipata/scipdf_parser.git), run the following commands:\n81:bash serve_grobid.sh\n84:(Optional) Or, you can refer to the following process to install grobid if the previous commands fail:\n86:git clone https://github.com/kermitt2/grobid.git\n87:cd grobid\n93:```python\n94:python main.py --topic {your research topic}\n97:## 📖 Evaluation Data\n100:## :black_nib: Citation\n===== code/discoverybench/README.md\n10:Dataset and code for [\"DiscoveryBench: Towards Data-Driven Discovery with Large Language Models\"](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2407.01725v1)\n14:## 🔭 Overview\n33:## 🚀 Running Discovery Agents\n38:Usage: discovery_agent.py [OPTIONS] QUERY\n47:  --api_config TEXT             API config file, default is\n57:## ⚖️ Evaluating Discovery Agents\n62:Usage: discovery_eval.py [OPTIONS] QUERY\n75:## 🌟 Contributing to DiscoveryBench\n81:## 🤗 Huggingface\n86:## ✍️ Citation\n91:  title     = \"DiscoveryBench: Towards Data-Driven Discovery with Large Language Models\",\n===== code/idea_novelty_checker/README.md\n1:# Scientific Idea Novelty Evaluation\n10:## Setup Instructions\n12:### Option 1: Using Conda\n17:   conda env create -f environment.yml\n21:   conda activate nc_env\n24:### Option 2: Using pip and virtualenv (or venv)\n28:   python3 -m venv nc_env\n34:3. **Install Dependencies:**  \n36:   pip install -r requirements.txt\n39:### Setup Keys and Default Parameters\n40:Add `OPENAI_API_KEY` or `ANTHROPIC_AP_KEY` and `S2_API_KEY` in the config.yml file. \n43:python noveltychecker/utils/load_env.py\n46:### More Instructions \n48:- The embedding-based reranking uses huggingface/allenai/specter2_base model. For low latency, run this novelty checker on a gpu. Incase, gpu is unavailable, one can use an API based embedding model (semantic scholar embedding api with specter-1) and change this in the reranker/embedding.py \n50:## Example Run\n56:python main.py --idea \"Hierarchical Topic Models (HTMs) are useful for discovering topic hierarchies in a collection of documents. However, traditional HTMs often produce hierarchies where lower-level topics are unrelated and not specific enough to their higher-level topics. Additionally, these methods can be computationally expensive. We present HyHTM - a Hyperbolic geometry based Hierarchical Topic Models - that addresses these limitations by incorporating hierarchical information from hyperbolic geometry to explicitly model hierarchies in topic models. Experimental results with four baselines show that HyHTM can better attend to parent-child relationships among topics. HyHTM produces coherent topic hierarchies that specialize in granularity from generic higher-level topics to specific lower-level topics. Further, our model is significantly faster and leaves a much smaller memory footprint than our best-performing baseline. We have made the source code for our algorithm publicly accessible.\" --papers \"220046811, 267211735\" --save_path \"example_path\" \n59:### Parameters\n70:### Idea Novelty Checker config\n74:#### Retrieval Settings\n77:  - `\"snippet\"`: Retrieves literature snippets and corresponding papers with similar claims using Semantic Scholar's snippet API.\n78:  - `\"keyword+title\"`: Uses an LLM (`DEFAULT_MODEL`) to extract keywords and titles from the idea, then fetches papers using Semantic Scholar's query search API.\n81:#### RankGPT Settings\n92:#### Novelty Checker Settings\n100:#### Other Settings\n107:## Contributing\n===== code/ideabench/README.md\n1:# IdeaBench\n5:## Using IdeaBench👇\n7:### 1. Setting up the Environment\n9:\t* Create a conda environment with required packages by running the following command in the terminal:\n10:\t* `conda env create -f environment.yml`\n12:\t* `conda activate ideabench_env`\n14:### 2. Configuration\n16:\t* In `src/build_dataset.sh`, `src/pipeline.sh`, `src/ablation_study.sh`, and `src/analyze_results.sh` set the `base_path` variable to be the path to the directory in where the repository is in. \n17:2. Set up your API keys. \n18:\t* To be able to generate and evaluate research ideas using this repository, it its necessary to obtain at least an [OpenAI API key](https://platform.openai.com/docs/overview). If you wish to use the Gemini models or Llama 3.1 models to generate research ideas, you need to additionally have a [Google AI](https://ai.google.dev/gemini-api/docs/api-key) or a [DeepInfra](https://deepinfra.com/) API key respectively. Add the applicable API keys in the same bash scripts mentioned earlier.\n20:### 3.  Building the Dataset (optional)\n24:### 4. Generating and Evaluating Research Ideas\n25:* To generate research ideas and evaluate them, you can use `pipeline.sh`.\n26:* First set up how you want to generate research ideas by editing the following variables in `src/pipeline.sh`:\n42:* When you are done configuring `src/pipeline.sh`, execute the bash script in your terminal by running `./pipeline.sh`. \n43:### 5. Analyzing Results \n51:### Note on API rate limits.\n52:* Each API has their own respective rate limits.\n53:* To avoid getting rate limit errors, it is recommended to avoid executing multiple `pipeline.sh` commands as once since multiple processes of generating and evaluating research ideas will be using your API concurrently.  If you do decide to do this, be careful that you do not surpass your rate limit, otherwise you will encounter issues. \n===== code/liveideabench/README.md\n1:# 🤖💡 [LiveIdeaBench](http://liveideabench.com): Evaluating LLMs' Scientific Creativity and Idea Generation with Minimal Context\n17:### 🤗 Dataset\n19:[![Hugging Face Models](https://img.shields.io/badge/%F0%9F%A4%97%20Hugging%20Face-Dataset_V1-yellow)](https://huggingface.co/datasets/6cf/liveideabench) [![Hugging Face Models](https://img.shields.io/badge/%F0%9F%A4%97%20Hugging%20Face-Dataset_V1_DLC_250127-yellow)](https://huggingface.co/datasets/6cf/liveideabench-DLC-250127) [![Hugging Face Models](https://img.shields.io/badge/%F0%9F%A4%97%20Hugging%20Face-Dataset_V2-yellow)](https://huggingface.co/datasets/6cf/liveideabench-v2)\n21:### 🧠✨🎉 News (2026/2/22): Our paper has been accepted by Nature Communications!\n29:### 🧠✨🎉 News (2025/3/29): Latest Dataset Update (v2) on Hugging Face! \n35:### 🧠✨🎉 News (2025/1/27): Latest Dataset Update on Hugging Face! \n41:## LiveIdeaBench Evaluation Framework\n45:## 👇 Evaluation Instruction\n47:### 1️⃣ Install Environment\n50:pip install -r requirements.txt\n53:### 2️⃣ Database Initialization\n55:Run the Python script to initialize the database:\n57:python -c \"from utils.database import init_database; init_database()\"\n60:### 3️⃣ Configuring API Keys\n62:Before running the program, you need to configure at least one API key:\n64:1. Create an `apikey` file and write your OpenRouter API key:\n71:   export OPENROUTER_API_KEY=\"your-openrouter-api-key\"\n72:   export STEP_API_KEY=\"your-step-api-key\"\n73:   export GEMINI_API_KEYS=\"key1,key2,key3\"\n76:### 4️⃣ Running Examples\n81:# Generate ideas using a specified model\n82:python run.py --idea_model \"openai/gpt-4o-mini\"\n84:# Use a specific provider\n85:python run.py --idea_model \"openai/gpt-4o-mini\" --provider openrouter\n89:# Use a single keyword:\n91:python run.py --idea_model \"openai/gpt-4o-mini\" --keyword \"relativity\"\n92:# Use multiple keywords:\n94:python run.py --idea_model \"openai/gpt-4o-mini\" --keyword \"relativity\" \"periodic table\"\n95:# Do not specify a keyword (use all keywords):\n97:python run.py --idea_model \"openai/gpt-4o-mini\"\n100:### 5️⃣ Database Export\n104:Run the script:\n107:python view_database.py      \n114:### 6️⃣ Evaluate Fluency\n118:Run the script:\n121:python hash.py\n124:### 7️⃣ Compute Flexibility & Plotting\n130:Run the Jupyter Notebook:  `stats_flexibility.ipynb`\n134:## 🌍🌱 CO2 Emission Estimation\n136:This repo provides an estimation of the CO2 footprint associated with running the idea generation and evaluation pipeline.\n138:Run the Jupyter Notebook: `co2.ipynb`\n141:## Bibtex\n===== code/mlagentbench/README.md\n1:# MLAgentBench: Evaluating Language Agents on Machine Learning Experimentation\n17:# Setup\n21:pip install -e .\n24:Install dependencies with python 3.10 by running \n34:2. Run the docker container from the image, mounting the current directory to `/MLAgentBench` inside the container with root user permissions to install other packages:\n46:python -u -m MLAgentBench.prepare_task <task_name> $(which python)\n48:For Kaggle datasets, you need to set up Kaggle API and authentication (~/.kaggle/kaggle.json) as described [here](https://www.kaggle.com/docs/api). You may also need to provide manual consent to the rules of specific competitions by following the prompts. For docker, use the following instructions:\n49:1. Ensure that you have \".kaggle/kaggle.json\" with your API credentials in the MLAgentBench root folder.\n53:pip install kaggle\n57:Finally, put API keys under the root directory of this repo (or wherever you run scripts from). Currently, we support OpenAI (openai_api_key.txt in the format of organization:APIkey), Claude (claude_api_key.txt), and CRFM API (crfm_api_key.txt). To use an AutoGPT agent, setup the directory as described [here](https://docs.agpt.co/setup/).\n61:# Quick Start\n63:To run our research agent on cifar10 task with openai API using gpt-4 and gpt-3.5-turbo:\n66:python -u -m MLAgentBench.runner --python $(which python) --task cifar10 --device 0 --log-dir first_test  --work-dir workspace --llm-name gpt-4 --edit-script-llm-name gpt-4 --fast-llm-name gpt-3.5-turbo >  first_test/log 2>&1\n88:# Evaluation\n92:python -m MLAgentBench.eval --log-folder <log_folder>  --task <task_name> --output-file <output_name>\n100:python -u -m MLAgentBench.runner --python $(which python) --task cifar10 --device 0 --log-dir first_test  --work-dir workspace --agent_type Agent\n105:# Workflow\n109:1. Run parallel experiments over different tasks and different agents using `run_experiments.sh`. This will generate log folders in structure of final_exp_logs/<model_name>/<run_timestamp>/...\n110:2. Run baseline.sh on all tasks to provide baselines.\n111:2. Run eval.sh with properly specified models and tasks to generate evaluation jsons, including baselines.\n114:# Tasks\n116:Each task is a folder in `MLAgentBench/benchmarks/`, under which the `env/` folder contains files that the research agent will see at the beginning, and `script/` folder contains additional hidden files such as `prepare.py` for downloading data and `eval.py` for evaluation.\n118:# Agents\n122:# Results\n135:# Interactive Mode (Under construction)\n===== code/researchagent/README.md\n1:# ResearchAgent: Iterative Research Idea Generation over Scientific Literature\n4:[![Python](https://img.shields.io/badge/Python-3.9%2B-orange)](https://www.python.org/downloads/release/python-390/)\n13:## Overview\n15:- Inputs: a set of Semantic Scholar paper IDs and a knowledge store mined from papers (entities and co-occurrences).\n16:- Retrieval: fetch the target paper, pull relevant references via the Semantic Scholar Graph API, and select related entities from the knowledge store.\n22:## Repository structure\n25:\t- main.py — entrypoint to run the end-to-end pipeline\n30:\t- pipelines/\n31:\t\t- research_pipeline.py — orchestration of generate and validate iterations\n38:\t\t- s2.py — Semantic Scholar API helpers (papers, references, embeddings)\n46:## Running\n48:Set your OpenAI key and run the pipeline:\n51:export OPENAI_API_KEY=[REDACTED] ./code/main.py \\\n59:## Citation\n===== code/rinobench/README.md\n1:# Is this Idea Novel? An Automated Benchmark for Judgment of Research Ideas 🦏\n3:> Repository of the LREC 2026 paper *\"Is this Idea Novel? An Automated Benchmark for Judgment of Research Ideas\"* 📄.\n7:📄 Paper:  [Is this Idea Novel? An Automated Benchmark for Judgment of Research Ideas (LREC 2026)](https://lrec.elra.info/lrec2026-main-370)\n9:🤗 Data: [https://huggingface.co/datasets/TimSchopf/RINoBench](https://huggingface.co/datasets/TimSchopf/RINoBench)\n11:## 🦏 Overview\n22:## 📂 Repository Structure\n40:└── requirements.txt  \n43:## 💾 Data Description\n53:## Citation information\n59:  title = {Is This Idea Novel? An Automated Benchmark for Judgment of Research Ideas},\n69:  abstract = {Judging the novelty of research ideas is crucial for advancing science, enabling the identification of unexplored directions, and ensuring contributions meaningfully extend existing knowledge rather than reiterate minor variations. However, given the exponential growth of scientific literature, manually judging the novelty of research ideas through literature reviews is labor-intensive, subjective, and infeasible at scale. Therefore, recent efforts have proposed automated approaches for research idea novelty judgment. Yet, evaluation of these approaches remains largely inconsistent and is typically based on non-standardized human evaluations, hindering large-scale, comparable evaluations. To address this, we introduce RINoBench, the first comprehensive benchmark for large-scale evaluation of research idea novelty judgments. It comprises 1,381 research ideas derived from and judged by human experts as well as nine automated evaluation metrics designed to assess both rubric-based novelty scores and textual justifications of novelty judgments. Using this benchmark, we evaluate several state-of-the-art large language models (LLMs) on their ability to judge the novelty of research ideas. Our findings reveal that while LLM-generated reasoning closely mirrors human rationales, this alignment does not reliably translate into accurate novelty judgments, which diverge significantly from human gold standard judgments—even among leading reasoning-capable models. Data and code available at: https://github.com/TimSchopf/RINoBench}\n===== code/scienceagentbench/README.md\n1:# ScienceAgentBench\n3:Code and data for the paper \"[ScienceAgentBench: Toward Rigorous Assessment of Language Agents for Data-Driven Scientific Discovery](https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.05080)\".\n8:[<a href=\"https://huggingface.co/datasets/osunlp/ScienceAgentBench\">Benchmark</a>] •\n12:## Updates:\n17:- 2024/10/24: Benchmark released. Updated the manuscript with OpenAI o1 results and case studies.\n20:## Table of Contents\n22:- [Benchmark Access](#benchmark-access)\n23:- [Setup](#setup)\n31:## ScienceAgentBench Summary\n40:## Benchmark Access\n44:To evaluate the agent outcomes, i.e. generated code, please download the full benchmark [here](https://buckeyemailosu-my.sharepoint.com/:u:/g/personal/chen_8336_buckeyemail_osu_edu/IQB870QrmuqwS5Ck33cHpJfkAVt3LsMeariREIwP3AT7byA?e=IpASb7) and unzip it with password `scienceagentbench`.\n48:After downloading and unzipping the full benchmark under this repository, the directory structure should look like this:\n66:## Setup\n68:### Environment\n70:To start, please create a conda environment and install the necessary packages as follows:\n72:conda create -n sci-agent python=3.10 pip setuptools wheel\n73:conda activate sci-agent\n74:pip install -r requirements.txt\n82:Additionally, to run the self-debug agent and evaluate generated code, we also need to create another environment `sci-agent-eval`. This environment leverages `pip-tools` to update its package installations automatically for different tasks.\n84:conda create -n sci-agent-eval python=3.10 pip setuptools wheel\n85:conda activate sci-agent-eval\n86:pip install pip-tools\n87:conda deactivate\n89:After installing `pip-tools`, please deactivate the environment. We need to keep `sci-agent-eval` clean and will only work in `sci-agent`.\n91:### LLM Access\n96:export OPENAI_API_KEY=[REDACTED] Code Generation with Agents\n108:### Direct Prompting and Self-Debug\n111:python -u run_infer.py \\\n122:### OpenHands CodeAct\n126:## Evaluation of Generated Code\n128:### Extract Code Files from Agent Logs\n131:python -u recover_pred_from_log.py \\\n138:### Evaluating Code Files\n144:Adapted from [SWE-bench](https://github.com/swe-bench/SWE-bench), the dockerized evaluation supports automatical environment setup and parallel execution. Run the following commands:\n147:pip install docker  # install Docker SDK for Python\n149:export OPENAI_API_KEY=[REDACTED] -m evaluation.harness.run_evaluation \\\n159:- `pred_program_path`: the path to the predicted program folder. You may first use `python recover_pred_from_log.py` to extract all the pred_programs and then specify the path.\n175:export OPENAI_API_KEY=[REDACTED] -u run_eval.py \\\n180:A valid OpenAI API key is required since our evaluation leverages GPT-4o to judge output visualizations.\n182:### Calculating Metrics\n185:python calculate_metrics.py \\\n198:## Contact\n202:## Licensing Information\n209:## Disclaimer\n213:## Citation\n219:      title={ScienceAgentBench: Toward Rigorous Assessment of Language Agents for Data-Driven Scientific Discovery}, \n===== code/scimon_clbd/README.md\n1:# SciMON: Scientific Inspiration Machines Optimized for Novelty\n9:* [Requirements](#requirements)\n15:## Overview\n21:## Requirements\n23:### Environment \n29:### Environment Setup Instructions for NLP\n37:conda create -n pyt1.11 python=3.8.5\n40:Step 2: Install PyTorch with CUDA (optional)\n44:conda install pytorch==1.11 torchvision torchaudio cudatoolkit=11.3 -c pytorch\n47:Step 3: Install Python dependencies\n51:pip install -r requirements.txt\n54:### Environment Setup Instructions for biochemical\n62:conda create -n pyt2.2 python=3.10\n65:Step 2: Install PyTorch with CUDA (optional)\n69:conda install pytorch torchvision torchaudio pytorch-cuda=12.1 -c pytorch -c nvidia\n72:Step 3: Install Python dependencies\n76:pip install -r requirements1.txt\n79:### Data Setup\n87:### Data Preprocess\n93:### Data and Code Description\n104:### Results\n109:## Quickstart for NLP domain\n114:conda activate pyt1.11\n117:### Training\n125:#### Test\n142:python gpt4.py\n148:python calculate_sim.py\n149:python gpt4_iter1.py\n150:python calculate_sim1.py\n151:python gpt4_iter2.py\n154:## Quickstart for biochemical domain\n159:conda activate pyt2.2\n164:### Training\n172:#### Test\n176:python inf_generator.py \n179:# Citation\n===== code/scipip/README.md\n15:      <img src=\"https://img.shields.io/badge/python->=3.10.3-blue\" alt=\"Python version\">\n21:## Introduction\n29:## Updates\n38:## Prerequisites\n40:The following enviroments are tested under Ubuntu 22.04 with python>=3.10.3.\n42:1. **Install essential packages**, feel free to copy and paste the following commans into your terminal. After that, you can visit your Neo4j databse in a browser.\n45:   ## Install git-lfs\n49:   ## Create new conda environment scipip\n50:   conda env create -f environment.yml\n51:   conda activate scipip\n53:   ## Install Neo4j database\n54:   sudo apt install -y openjdk-17-jre # Install Neo4j required JDK\n55:   # cd ~/Downloads # or /your/path/to/download/Neo4j\n70:2. **Clone this repository (SciPIP) and edit the configuration files.** Specifically, LLMs' API token and the Neo4j' username/password are need configuring, and we have provided the template.\n77:   # Must be corrected: NEO4J_USERNAME / NEO4J_PASSWD / MODEL_API_KEY / MODEL_URL\n85:   1. Download the literature data from [google_drive](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1kZmJff8am-JGegZZQx0qxlC7o7YgBURg/view?usp=sharing) or [baidu disk](https://pan.baidu.com/s/1S22Evi5ReL0MvahFoQ-ipA?pwd=scip). Replace the `/your/path/neo4j-community-5.25.1/data` folder with our provided `data` folder, which contains literature of CV, NLP, ML, *etc.*\n86:   2. [Optional] Prepare the embedding model. Our algorithm uses **jina-embedding v3** and will automatically download it from Huggingface the first time the program is run. However, if you're concerned about potential download failures due to network issues, you can download it in advance and place it in the specified directory.\n94:## Run In a Browser (Recommended)\n98:# OR\n99:python -m streamlit run app.py\n103:## Run In a Terminal\n110:python src/generator.py new-idea --brainstorm-mode mode_c --use-inspiration True --num 2\n115:## Others\n117:### Database Construction\n120:wget https://github.com/explosion/spacy-models/releases/download/en_core_web_sm-3.7.1/en_core_web_sm-3.7.1-py3-none-any.whl\n121:pip install en_core_web_sm-3.7.1-py3-none-any.whl\n128:python src/paper_manager.py crawling --year all --venue-name nips\n136:python src/paper_manager.py update --year all --venue-name nips\n139:## Cite Us\n142:@article{wang2024scipip,\n151:## Help Us To Improve\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
